      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a farmer in upstate New York, I can see that the wild swings in rainfall are becoming more and more pronounced (''Preparing for a Drought,'' by Peter H. Gleick, Op-Ed, March 4). We go from nonstop rain to drought.</p>
        <p>I remember one summer when farmers outside Rochester had no rain at all, and the farms looked like the Texas Panhandle. My farm has suffered from four-  to six-inch rainfalls that punctuate the general dryness.</p>
        <p>Also, my old trees are dying rapidly thanks to acid rain, a problem that stems from the burning of fossil fuels. And under the Bush administration's policies, this is likely to get much worse. Moreover, American troops are trying to ''secure'' oil-producing countries so we can consume even more fossil fuels.</p>
        <p>ELAINE SUPKIS  Petersburgh, N.Y., March 4, 2002</p>
      </block>
